# Working with AgentStore

AgentStore is a shared datastore you reach through the `{{.App}}` command-line tool.
Think of it as Git with two extra powers: **file-level permissions** (you only see
and touch what you've been granted) and **live events** (you can watch a path and
react as others change it). Knowledge lives as files; every change is a commit;
commits sync to a remote server that enforces access control.

This skill teaches the core loops an agent runs with AgentStore — optionally
self-hosting a server, then onboarding, reading, contributing, and staying in sync —
plus the two failure modes that will otherwise trip you up. For exact command syntax
and every flag, read `reference/cli.md` next to this file — do not guess flags.

## Prerequisite — make sure `{{.App}}` is installed

First check whether it is already available: run `{{.App}} version`. If that prints a
version, skip ahead. If the command is not found, install it with **one** of the
options below, then run `{{.App}} version` again to confirm before continuing.

**Preferred — prebuilt binary** (no toolchain; lands on a directory that is on your `PATH`):

```
OS=$(uname -s | tr A-Z a-z); ARCH=$(uname -m); case $ARCH in x86_64) ARCH=amd64;; aarch64|arm64) ARCH=arm64;; esac
curl -fsSL "https://github.com/guyweissman/agentstore/releases/latest/download/{{.App}}_${OS}_${ARCH}.tar.gz" | tar -xz -C /usr/local/bin {{.App}} && {{.App}} version
```

If `/usr/local/bin` is not writable, extract into a directory you can write that is on
your `PATH` instead (e.g. `mkdir -p ~/.local/bin && export PATH="$PATH:$HOME/.local/bin"`,
then change the `-C` target to `~/.local/bin`).

**Alternative — `go install`** (only if Go is already installed):

```
go install github.com/guyweissman/agentstore/cmd/store@latest
```

This installs to `$(go env GOPATH)/bin` (usually `~/go/bin`). If `{{.App}} version`
still reports "not found" afterward, that directory is not on your `PATH` — add it with
`export PATH="$PATH:$(go env GOPATH)/bin"`, then re-check.

If both options fail to download, the binary is likely not published yet (the repo and
its releases must be public). Report that and stop — do not retry in a loop.

## Mental model

- A **repo** is a local checkout (`{{.StoreDir}}/` holds its state) backed by a **remote** server.
- You act as a **principal** (an identity) authenticated by an ed25519 key. Every
  request is signed; there are no passwords or tokens to paste.
- The server **filters reads by permission**. A short or empty listing is normal,
  not a bug — it means you have not been granted those paths.
- Writes are **commit → push**. The server uses optimistic concurrency: if someone
  else pushed first, your push is rejected and you reconcile (see Loop 4 below).

## Loop 0 — Self-host a server (optional)

If there is no remote yet, run one yourself — most setups start this way. The
server is a single binary and stores everything under one data directory.

1. Start it (defaults to `127.0.0.1:8080`, data in `~/{{.GlobalDir}}/server-data`):
   `{{.App}} server start`. It runs in the **foreground and blocks**, so launch it as
   a background process and confirm it is listening before continuing.
2. Use `http://127.0.0.1:8080` as the `<url>` in the loops below.
3. Create your first repo on it: `{{.App}} init <url> [<dir>]` (makes the repo server-side
   and checks it out locally).
4. Stop it when done: `{{.App}} server stop`.

Skip this loop entirely if you were given a remote URL — just use that instead.

## Loop 1 — Onboard once (identity)

You need an ed25519 keypair and a registered identity before anything else works.
Only the public key ever leaves your machine.

1. Generate a key (standard ssh-keygen, no passphrase for automation):
   `ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f ~/{{.GlobalDir}}/id -N ""`
2. Register it on the remote: `{{.App}} register --remote <url> --username <name> --public-key ~/{{.GlobalDir}}/id.pub`
3. Confirm who the server thinks you are: `{{.App}} whoami`

If you are joining a repo that already exists (or was moved), use `{{.App}} bind`
instead of `register` to point local config at your existing identity. To rotate a
key, use `{{.App}} rekey`.

## Loop 2 — Read shared knowledge

1. Get the repo: `{{.App}} clone <url>` (first time) or `{{.App}} pull` (refresh an existing checkout).
2. Inspect history and content: `{{.App}} log`, `{{.App}} show <commit>`, `{{.App}} diff`.
3. Retrieve an earlier version of a file or the whole repo: `{{.App}} checkout <commit|seq> <path|.>`.

**Critical:** reads are permission-filtered. If a file or directory you expect is
missing, the correct conclusion is "I may not have access," not "the data is gone."
Check `{{.App}} permissions <path>`; if you need access, you must ask a repo admin
for a grant — you cannot grant yourself.

## Loop 3 — Contribute knowledge

The write cycle is stage → commit → push:

1. `{{.App}} add <path>...` to stage new or changed files (`{{.App}} rm <path>` to stage a deletion).
2. `{{.App}} status` / `{{.App}} diff --staged` to confirm exactly what you're about to record.
3. `{{.App}} commit -m "why this change"` — commit messages describe intent, not mechanics.
4. `{{.App}} push` to publish to the remote.

Stage deliberately and keep commits focused — one logical change each. If you only
need to undo local, unpushed work, `{{.App}} reset` restores to the last pushed state.

## Loop 4 — Stay in sync and watch

To react to changes from other principals in real time:
`{{.App}} watch <path>` streams JSON events (one per line) for paths you can read.
Use it when you need to wait for or respond to another agent's contribution rather
than polling with repeated pulls.

## Failure playbook A — your push was rejected (conflict)

A rejected push means the remote moved since you last synced (optimistic
concurrency). Do **not** retry the same push in a loop. Instead:

1. `{{.App}} pull` — fetch the remote commits and merge.
2. If the merge needs attention, resolve it, then `{{.App}} commit`. To bail out of a
   half-finished merge, `{{.App}} merge --abort` restores your last committed state.
3. `{{.App}} push` again.

## Failure playbook B — permission denied

If a read returns nothing it shouldn't, or a write/grant is refused, you've hit the
access control boundary. You cannot fix this yourself. Report clearly what path and what
operation was denied so a repo admin (or owner) can `{{.App}} grant` you `read`,
`write`, or `owner` on that path. Admins manage membership with `{{.App}} principals`
and the admin role with `{{.App}} admin`.

## Notes for agents

- Prefer JSON output where offered (e.g. `watch` is JSON; `status` and others accept
  `--json`) so you can parse rather than scrape.
- Never invent flags or subcommands. The authoritative surface is `reference/cli.md`;
  when in doubt run `{{.App}} <command> --help`.
- Setup commands (`register`, `bind`, `rekey`) touch identity and config — run them
  once and confirm with `{{.App}} whoami` rather than repeating them.
